# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chibios
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chibios/board-support-package] The board support package is usually provided by the SoC manufacturer (such as Qualcomm), and may be modified by the OEM.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] Third-party hardware developers who wish to support a given embedded operating system must create a BSP that allows that embedded operating system to run on their platform.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] In most cases, the embedded operating system image—containing the BSP, software license, and hardware support—is bundled together by the hardware vendor.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] BSPs are typically customizable, allowing the user to specify which drivers and routines should be included in the build based on their selection of hardware and software options.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] For instance, a particular single-board computer might be paired with several peripheral chips; in that case the BSP might include drivers for peripheral chips supported; when building the BSP image the user would specify which peripheral drivers to include based on their choice of hardware.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] Some suppliers also provide a root file system, a toolchain for building programs to run on the embedded system, and utilities to configure the device (while running) along with the BSP.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] Many embedded operating system providers provide template BSP's, developer assistance, and test suites to aid BSP developers to set up an embedded operating system on a new hardware platform.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] The term *BSP* has been in use since 1981 when Hunter & Ready, the developers of the Versatile Real-Time Executive (VRTX), first coined the term to describe the hardware-dependent software needed to run VRTX on a specific hardware platform.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] Since the 1980s, it has been in wide use throughout the industry.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] Virtually all RTOS providers now use the term BSP.
[src:chibios/board-support-package] In modern systems, the term has been extended to refer to packages that only deal with one processor, not the whole motherboard.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] Commercial licenses are available from *ChibiOS*.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] Additional products include ChibiOS/HAL, a hardware abstraction layer compatible with ChibiOS/RT, and ChibiStudio, a free integrated development environment based on Eclipse, the GNU Compiler Collection, and the OpenOCD Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) debugging pod.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] ChibiOS/RT is designed for embedded applications on microcontrollers of 8-, 16-, and 32-bits.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] Size and execution efficiency are the main project goals.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] As reference, the kernel size can range from a minimum of 1.2 KiB up to a maximum of 5.5 KiB with all the subsystems activated on a STM32 Cortex-M3 processor.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] The kernel can achieve over 220,000 created/terminated threads per second and can perform a context switch in 1.2 microseconds on an STM32 @ 72 MHz.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] Similar metrics for all the supported platforms are included in the source code distribution as test reports.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] All system objects, such as threads, semaphores, timers, etc., can be created and deleted at runtime.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] There is no upper limit except for the available memory.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] To increase system reliability, the kernel architecture is entirely static, a memory allocator is not needed (but is available as an option), and there are no data structures with upper size limits like tables or arrays.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] The system application programming interfaces (APIs) are designed to not have error conditions such as error codes or exceptions.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] Contributed ports are also available for the Coldfire and H8S families.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] ChibiOS/RT has also been ported to the Raspberry Pi and the following device drivers have been implemented: Port (GPIO), Serial, GPT (General-Purpose Timer), I2C, SPI and PWM.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] It is also possible to run the kernel in a Win32 process in a software I/O emulation mode, allowing easy application development without the need for physical hardware.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] An example is included for MinGW compiler.
[src:chibios/chibios-rt] ChibiOS/RT is fully supported by the graphical user interface (GUI) toolkit µGFX, formerly named ChibiOS/GFX.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:chibios/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:chibios/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A **microcontroller** (**MC**, **uC**, or **μC**) or **microcontroller unit** (**MCU**) is a small computer on a single integrated circuit.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A microcontroller contains one or more processor cores along with memory and programmable input/output peripherals.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Program memory in the form of NOR flash, OTP ROM, or ferroelectric RAM is also often included on the chip, as well as a small amount of RAM.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are designed for embedded applications, in contrast to the microprocessors used in personal computers or other general-purpose applications consisting of various discrete chips.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In modern terminology, a microcontroller is similar to, but less sophisticated than, a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A SoC may include a microcontroller as one of its components but usually integrates it with advanced peripherals like a graphics processing unit (GPU), a Wi-Fi module, or one or more coprocessors.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are used in automatically controlled products and devices, such as automobile engine control systems, implantable medical devices, remote controls, office machines, appliances, power tools, toys, and other embedded systems.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] By reducing the size and cost compared to a design that uses a separate microprocessor, memory, and input/output devices, microcontrollers make digital control of more devices and processes practical.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Mixed-signal microcontrollers are common, integrating analog components needed to control non-digital electronic systems.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In the context of the Internet of things, microcontrollers are an economical and popular means of data collection, sensing and actuating the physical world as edge devices.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers may use four-bit words and operate at frequencies as low as 4 kHz for low power consumption (single-digit milliwatts or microwatts).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] They generally have the ability to retain functionality while waiting for an event such as a button press or other interrupt; power consumption while sleeping (with the CPU clock and most peripherals off) may be just nanowatts, making many of them well suited for long lasting battery applications.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Other microcontrollers may serve performance-critical roles, where they may need to act more like a digital signal processor (DSP), with higher clock speeds and power consumption.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released on a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] It was followed by the 4-bit Intel 4040, the 8-bit Intel 8008, and the 8-bit Intel 8080.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] All of these processors required several external chips to implement a working system, including memory and peripheral interface chips.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] As a result, the total system cost was several hundred (1970s US) dollars, making it impossible to economically computerize small appliances.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] MOS Technology introduced its sub-$100 microprocessors in 1975, the 6501 and 6502.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Their chief aim was to reduce this cost barrier but these microprocessors still required external support, memory, and peripheral chips which kept the total system cost in the hundreds of dollars.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] One book credits TI engineers Gary Boone and Michael Cochran with the successful creation of the first microcontroller in 1971.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The result of their work was the TMS 1000, which became commercially available in 1974.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] It combined read-only memory, read/write memory, processor and clock on one chip and was targeted at embedded systems.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] During the early-to-mid-1970s, Japanese electronics manufacturers began producing microcontrollers for automobiles, including 4-bit MCUs for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, and dashboard, and 8-bit MCUs for engine control.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Partly in response to the existence of the single-chip TMS 1000, Intel developed a computer system on a chip optimized for control applications, the Intel 8048, with commercial parts first shipping in 1977.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] It combined RAM and ROM on the same chip with a microprocessor.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Among numerous applications, this chip would eventually find its way into over one billion PC keyboards.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Valenter, stated that the microcontroller was one of the most successful products in the company's history, and he expanded the microcontroller division's budget by over 25%.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Most microcontrollers at this time had concurrent variants.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] One had EPROM program memory, with a transparent quartz window in the lid of the package to allow it to be erased by exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] These erasable chips were often used for prototyping.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The other variant was either a mask-programmed ROM or a PROM variant which was only programmable once.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] For the latter, sometimes the designation *OTP* was used, standing for "one-time programmable".
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In an OTP microcontroller, the PROM was usually of identical type as the EPROM, but the chip package had no quartz window; because there was no way to expose the EPROM to ultraviolet light, it could not be erased.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Because the erasable versions required ceramic packages with quartz windows, they were significantly more expensive than the OTP versions, which could be made in lower-cost opaque plastic packages.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] For the erasable variants, quartz was required, instead of less expensive glass, for its transparency to ultraviolet light—to which glass is largely opaque—but the main cost differentiator was the ceramic package itself.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] **Piggyback microcontrollers** were also used.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In 1993, the introduction of EEPROM memory allowed microcontrollers (beginning with the Microchip PIC16C84) to be electrically erased quickly without an expensive package as required for EPROM, allowing both rapid prototyping, and in-system programming.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] (EEPROM technology had been available prior to this time, but the earlier EEPROM was more expensive and less durable, making it unsuitable for low-cost mass-produced microcontrollers.) The same year, Atmel introduced the first microcontroller using Flash memory, a special type of EEPROM.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Other companies rapidly followed suit, with both memory types.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Nowadays microcontrollers are cheap and readily available for hobbyists, with large online communities around certain processors.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In 2002, about 55% of all CPUs sold in the world were 8-bit microcontrollers and microprocessors.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Over two billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 1997, and according to Semico, over four billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 2006.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] More recently, Semico has claimed the MCU market grew 36.5% in 2010 and 12% in 2011.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A typical home in a developed country is likely to have only four general-purpose microprocessors but around three dozen microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A typical mid-range automobile has about 30 microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] They can also be found in many electrical devices such as washing machines, microwave ovens, and telephones.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Cost to manufacture can be under US$0.10 per unit.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Cost has plummeted over time, with the cheapest 8-bit microcontrollers being available for under US$0.03 in 2018, and some 32-bit microcontrollers around US$1 for similar quantities.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In 2012, following a global crisis—a worst ever annual sales decline and recovery and average sales price year-over-year plunging 17%—the biggest reduction since the 1980s—the average price for a microcontroller was US$0.88 (US$0.69 for 4-/8-bit, US$0.59 for 16-bit, US$1.76 for 32-bit).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In 2012, worldwide sales of 8-bit microcontrollers were around US$4 billion, while 4-bit microcontrollers also saw significant sales.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] On 21 June 2018, the "world's smallest computer" was announced by the University of Michigan.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Because they are too small to have conventional radio antennae, they receive and transmit data with visible light.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A microcontroller can be considered a self-contained system with a processor, memory and peripherals and can be used as an embedded system.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The majority of microcontrollers in use today are embedded in other machinery, such as automobiles, telephones, appliances, and peripherals for computer systems.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] While some embedded systems are very sophisticated, many have minimal requirements for memory and program length, with no operating system, and low software complexity.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Typical input and output devices include switches, relays, solenoids, LEDs, small or custom liquid-crystal displays, radio frequency devices, and sensors for data such as temperature, humidity, light level etc.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Embedded systems usually have no keyboard, screen, disks, printers, or other recognizable I/O devices of a personal computer, and may lack human interaction devices of any kind.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers must provide real-time (predictable, though not necessarily fast) response to events in the embedded system they are controlling.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Possible interrupt sources are device-dependent and often include events such as an internal timer overflow, completing an analog-to-digital conversion, a logic-level change on an input such as from a button being pressed, and data received on a communication link.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Where power consumption is important as in battery devices, interrupts may also wake a microcontroller from a low-power sleep state where the processor is halted until required to do something by a peripheral event.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Typically microcontroller programs must fit in the available on-chip memory, since it would be costly to provide a system with external, expandable memory.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Compilers and assemblers are used to convert both high-level and assembly language code into a compact machine code for storage in the microcontroller's memory.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Depending on the device, the program memory may be permanent, read-only memory that can only be programmed at the factory, or it may be field-alterable flash or erasable read-only memory.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Manufacturers have often produced special versions of their microcontrollers in order to help the hardware and software development of the target system.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Originally these included EPROM versions that have a "window" on the top of the device through which program memory can be erased by ultraviolet light, ready for reprogramming after a programming ("burn") and test cycle.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Since 1998, EPROM versions are rare and have been replaced by EEPROM and flash, which are easier to use (can be erased electronically) and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Other versions may be available where the ROM is accessed as an external device rather than as internal memory, however these are becoming rare due to the widespread availability of cheap microcontroller programmers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The use of field-programmable devices on a microcontroller may allow field update of the firmware or permit late factory revisions to products that have been assembled but not yet shipped.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Programmable memory also reduces the lead time required for deployment of a new product.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Where hundreds of thousands of identical devices are required, using parts programmed at the time of manufacture can be economical.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] These "mask-programmed" parts have the program laid down in the same way as the logic of the chip, at the same time.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A customized microcontroller incorporates a block of digital logic that can be personalized for additional processing capability, peripherals and interfaces that are adapted to the requirements of the application.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers usually contain from several to dozens of general purpose input/output pins (GPIO).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] GPIO pins are software configurable to either an input or an output state.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] When GPIO pins are configured to an input state, they are often used to read sensors or external signals.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Configured to the output state, GPIO pins can drive external devices such as LEDs or motors, often indirectly, through external power electronics.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Many embedded systems need to read sensors that produce analog signals.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] However, because they are built to interpret and process digital data, i.e.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] 1s and 0s, they are not able to do anything with the analog signals that may be sent to it by a device.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] So, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is used to convert the incoming data into a form that the processor can recognize.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A less common feature on some microcontrollers is a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that allows the processor to output analog signals or voltage levels.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In addition to the converters, many embedded microprocessors include a variety of timers as well.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] One of the most common types of timers is the programmable interval timer (PIT).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A PIT may either count down from some value to zero, or up to the capacity of the count register, overflowing to zero.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Once it reaches zero, it sends an interrupt to the processor indicating that it has finished counting.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] This is useful for devices such as thermostats, which periodically test the temperature around them to see if they need to turn the air conditioner on/off, the heater on/off, etc.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A dedicated pulse-width modulation (PWM) block makes it possible for the CPU to control power converters, resistive loads, motors, etc., without using many CPU resources in tight timer loops.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A universal asynchronous receiver/transmitter (UART) block makes it possible to receive and transmit data over a serial line with very little load on the CPU.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Dedicated on-chip hardware also often includes capabilities to communicate with other devices (chips) in digital formats such as Inter-Integrated Circuit (I²C), Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI), Universal Serial Bus (USB), and Ethernet.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers may not implement an external address or data bus as they integrate RAM and non-volatile memory on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Using fewer pins, the chip can be placed in a much smaller, cheaper package.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Integrating the memory and other peripherals on a single chip and testing them as a unit increases the cost of that chip, but often results in decreased net cost of the embedded system as a whole.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] This integration drastically reduces the number of chips and the amount of wiring and circuit board space that would be needed to produce equivalent systems using separate chips.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Furthermore, on low pin count devices in particular, each pin may interface to several internal peripherals, with the pin function selected by software.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] This allows a part to be used in a wider variety of applications than if pins had dedicated functions.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers have proved to be highly popular in embedded systems since their introduction in the 1970s.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers use a Harvard architecture: separate memory buses for instructions and data, allowing accesses to take place concurrently.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Where a Harvard architecture is used, instruction words for the processor may be a different bit size than the length of internal memory and registers; for example: 12-bit instructions used with 8-bit data registers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The decision of which peripheral to integrate is often difficult.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The microcontroller vendors often trade operating frequencies and system design flexibility against time-to-market requirements from their customers and overall lower system cost.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Manufacturers have to balance the need to minimize the chip size against additional functionality.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontroller architectures vary widely.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Some designs include general-purpose microprocessor cores, with one or more ROM, RAM, or I/O functions integrated onto the package.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Other designs are purpose-built for control applications.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A microcontroller instruction set usually has many instructions intended for bit manipulation (bit-wise operations) to make control programs more compact.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] For example, a general-purpose processor might require several instructions to test a bit in a register and branch if the bit is set, where a microcontroller could have a single instruction to provide that commonly required function.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers historically have not had math coprocessors, so floating-point arithmetic has been performed by software.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] However, some recent designs do include FPUs and DSP-optimized features.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] An example would be Microchip's PIC32 MIPS-based line.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers were originally programmed only in assembly language, but various high-level programming languages, such as C, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Compilers for general-purpose languages will typically have some restrictions as well as enhancements to better support the unique characteristics of microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers have environments to aid developing certain types of applications.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontroller vendors often make tools freely available to make it easier to adopt their hardware.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Microcontrollers with specialty hardware may require their own non-standard dialects of C, such as SDCC for the 8051, which prevent using standard tools (such as code libraries or static analysis tools) even for code unrelated to hardware features.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Interpreters may also contain nonstandard features, such as MicroPython, although a fork, CircuitPython, has looked to move hardware dependencies to libraries and have the language adhere to a more CPython standard.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Interpreter firmware is also available for some microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] For example, BASIC on the early microcontroller Intel 8052; BASIC and FORTH on the Zilog Z8 as well as some modern devices.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Typically these interpreters support interactive programming.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Simulators are available for some microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] These allow a developer to analyze what the behavior of the microcontroller and their program should be if they were using the actual part.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A simulator will show the internal processor state and also that of the outputs, as well as allowing input signals to be generated.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] While on the one hand most simulators will be limited from being unable to simulate much other hardware in a system, they can exercise conditions that may otherwise be hard to reproduce at will in the physical implementation, and can be the quickest way to debug and analyze problems.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Recent microcontrollers are often integrated with on-chip debug circuitry that when accessed by an in-circuit emulator (ICE) via JTAG, allow debugging of the firmware with a debugger.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A real-time ICE may allow viewing and/or manipulating of internal states while running.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A tracing ICE can record executed program and MCU states before/after a trigger point.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Many others exist, some of which are used in very narrow range of applications or are more like applications processors than microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The microcontroller market is extremely fragmented, with numerous vendors, technologies, and markets.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Note that many vendors sell or have sold multiple architectures.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In contrast to general-purpose computers, microcontrollers used in embedded systems often seek to optimize interrupt latency over instruction throughput.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Issues include both reducing the latency, and making it be more predictable (to support real-time control).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] When an electronic device causes an interrupt, during the context switch the intermediate results (registers) have to be saved before the software responsible for handling the interrupt can run.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] They must also be restored after that interrupt handler is finished.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] If there are more processor registers, this saving and restoring process may take more time, increasing the latency.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Another technique involves spending silicon gates on "shadow registers": One or more duplicate registers used only by the interrupt software, perhaps supporting a dedicated stack.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Lower end microcontrollers tend to support fewer interrupt latency controls than higher end ones.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Two different kinds of memory are commonly used with microcontrollers, a non-volatile memory for storing firmware and a read–write memory for temporary data.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] From the earliest microcontrollers to today, six-transistor SRAM is almost always used as the read/write working memory, with a few more transistors per bit used in the register file.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] In addition to the SRAM, some microcontrollers also have internal EEPROM and/or NVRAM for data storage; and ones that do not have any (such as the BASIC Stamp), or where the internal memory is insufficient, are often connected to an external EEPROM or flash memory chip.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] A few microcontrollers beginning in 2003 have "self-programmable" flash memory.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] The earliest microcontrollers used mask ROM to store firmware.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Later microcontrollers (such as the early versions of the Freescale 68HC11 and early PIC microcontrollers) had EPROM memory, which used a translucent window to allow erasure via UV light, while production versions had no such window, being OTP (one-time-programmable).
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Firmware updates were equivalent to replacing the microcontroller itself, thus many products were not upgradeable.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Motorola MC68HC805 was the first microcontroller to use EEPROM to store the firmware.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] EEPROM microcontrollers became more popular in 1993 when Microchip introduced PIC16C84 and Atmel introduced an 8051-core microcontroller that was first one to use NOR Flash memory to store the firmware.
[src:chibios/microcontroller] Today's microcontrollers almost all use flash memory, with a few models using FRAM and some ultra-low-cost parts still using OTP or mask ROM.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:chibios/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:chibios/stm32] In addition to its microcontroller lines, STMicroelectronics has introduced microprocessor (MPU) offerings such as the MP1 and MP2 series into the STM32 family.
[src:chibios/stm32] These processors are based around single or dual ARM Cortex-A cores combined with an ARM Cortex-M core.
[src:chibios/stm32] Cortex-A application processors include a memory management unit (MMU), enabling them to run advanced operating systems such as Linux.
[src:chibios/stm32] The **STM32** family of the microcontroller ICs is based on various 32-bit RISC ARM Cortex-M cores.
[src:chibios/stm32] STMicroelectronics licenses the ARM Processor IP from ARM Holdings and integrates them with custom-designed peripherals to create complete microcontroller solutions.
[src:chibios/stm32] Each STM32 microcontroller is designed for specific performance, power efficiency, and feature requirements, making them suitable for a wide range of embedded applications.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following tables summarize the STM32 family of microcontrollers (MCUs) and microprocessors (MPUs).
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 is the third ARM family by STMicroelectronics.
[src:chibios/stm32] It follows their earlier STR9 family based on the ARM9E core, and STR7 family based on the ARM7TDMI core.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following is the history of how the STM32 family has evolved.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 family consists of many series of microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/stm32] Each STM32 microcontroller series is based upon a specific ARM Cortex-M processor core.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 F0-series are the first group of ARM Cortex-M0 chips in the STM32 family.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 F1-series was the first group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M3 core and considered their mainstream ARM microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/stm32] The F1-series has evolved over time by increasing CPU speed, size of internal memory, variety of peripherals.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 F2-series of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M3 core.
[src:chibios/stm32] It is the most recent and fastest Cortex-M3 series.
[src:chibios/stm32] The F2 is pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F4-series.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 F3-series is the second group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M4F core.
[src:chibios/stm32] The F3 is almost pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F1-series.
[src:chibios/stm32] The distinguishing feature for this series is presence of four fast, 12-bit, simultaneous sampling ADCs (multiplexer to over 30 channels), and four matched, 8 MHz bandwidth op-amps with all pins exposed and additionally internal PGA (Programmable Gain Array) network.
[src:chibios/stm32] The exposed pads allow for a range of analog signal conditioning circuits like band-pass filters, anti-alias filters, charge amplifiers, integrators/differentiators, 'instrumentation' high-gain differential inputs, and other.
[src:chibios/stm32] This eliminates need for external op-amps for many applications.
[src:chibios/stm32] The built-in two-channel DAC has arbitrary waveform as well as a hardware-generated waveform (sine, triangle, noise etc.) capability.
[src:chibios/stm32] All analog devices can be completely independent, or partially internally connected, meaning that one can have nearly everything that is needed for an advanced measurement and sensor interfacing system in a single chip.
[src:chibios/stm32] The four ADCs can be simultaneously sampled making a wide range of precision analog control equipment possible.
[src:chibios/stm32] It is also possible to use a hardware scheduler for the multiplexer array, allowing good timing accuracy when sampling more than 4 channels, independent of the main processor thread.
[src:chibios/stm32] The sampling and multiplexing trigger can be controlled from a variety of sources including timers and built-in comparators, allowing for irregular sampling intervals where needed.
[src:chibios/stm32] STM32F37/38xxx integrate a 14-effective number of bits delta-sigma ADC.
[src:chibios/stm32] The op-amps inputs feature 2-to-1 analog multiplexer, allowing for a total of eight analog channels to be pre-processed using the op-amp; all the op-amp outputs can be internally connected to ADCs.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 F4-series is the first group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M4F core.
[src:chibios/stm32] The F4-series is also the first STM32 series to have DSP and floating-point instructions.
[src:chibios/stm32] The F4 is pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F2-series and adds higher clock speed, 64 KB CCM static RAM, full-duplex I²S, improved real-time clock, and faster ADCs.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 F7-series is a group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M7F core.
[src:chibios/stm32] Many of the F7 series are pin-to-pin compatible with the STM32 F4-series.
[src:chibios/stm32] Many of STM32F76xxx and STM32F77xxx models have a digital filter for sigma-delta modulators (DFSDM) interface.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 H7-series is a group of high performance STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M7F core with double-precision floating point unit and optional second Cortex-M4F core with single-precision floating point.
[src:chibios/stm32] Cortex-M7F core can reach working frequency up to 600 MHz, while Cortex-M4F - up to 240 MHz.
[src:chibios/stm32] Each of these cores can work independently or as master/slave core.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 L0-series is the first group of STM32 microcontrollers based on the ARM Cortex-M0+ core.
[src:chibios/stm32] This series targets low power applications.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 L1-series was the first group of STM32 microcontrollers with a primary goal of ultra-low power usage for battery-powered applications.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 L4-series is an evolution of STM32L1-series of ultra-low power microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM32 L4+-series is expansion of STM32L4-series of ultra-low power microcontrollers, providing more performance, more embedded memory and richer graphics and connectivity features while keeping ultra-low-power capability.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following boards have Arduino Nano pin-compatible male pin headers with 0.6-inch row-to-row DIP-30 footprint, but these boards have 3.3 volt logic I/O, instead of 5 volt logic I/O for an Arduino Nano "R3" and Nano R4.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following boards have Arduino Uno R3 pin-compatible female pin headers for Arduino shields, but these boards have 3.3 volt logic I/O, instead of 5 volt logic I/O for an Arduino Uno.
[src:chibios/stm32] There are three Nucleo board types, each supporting a different STM32 IC package footprint.
[src:chibios/stm32] As of fall 2025, there were over eighty Nucleo board variations: 9 of Nucleo-32, 39 of Nucleo-64, 28 of Nucleo-144; 1 obsolete Nucleo-32, 5 obsolete Nucleo-144.
[src:chibios/stm32] All Nucleo boards by STMicroelectronics have an additional onboard ST-LINK host adapter chip which supplies SWD debugging, virtual COM port, and mass storage over USB.
[src:chibios/stm32] The debugger embedded on Nucleo boards can be converted to the SEGGER J-Link debugger protocol.
[src:chibios/stm32] Though some STM32 microcontrollers have a real-time clock (RTC) peripheral and/or battery-back SRAM, none of the Nucleo boards have a battery holder.
[src:chibios/stm32] Nucleo-32 boards have 32-pin STM32 ICs and Arduino Nano pin-compatible male pin headers with 0.6-inch row-to-row DIP-30 footprint.
[src:chibios/stm32] Nucleo-64 boards have 64-pin STM32 ICs (except Nucleo-C031C6 and Nucleo-C051C8 have 48-pin ICs), Arduino Uno R3 female headers for shields, ST Morpho male pin headers (two 19x2), some board have a second USB connector, one board (NUCLEO-C092RC) has a CAN-FD bus connector.
[src:chibios/stm32] Nucleo-144 boards have 144-pin STM32 ICs (except Nucleo-H7S3L8 has 225-pin IC and Nucleo-N657X0-Q has 264-pin IC), Arduino Uno R3 female headers for shields, ST Zio female headers, ST Morpho male pin headers (two 19x2), some have a second USB connector, some have a RJ45 Ethernet connector.
[src:chibios/stm32] The unlisted Nucleo-F429ZI, Nucleo-F746ZG, Nucleo-H743ZI, Nucleo-H743ZI2, Nucleo-H745ZI-Q are obsolete.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following table compares various features of official Nucleo boards from STMicroelectronics.
[src:chibios/stm32] The left half of the table contains details about each board, the right half of the table contains details about the microcontroller (MCU) on each board.
[src:chibios/stm32] Table columns can be sorted by clicking on the arrows in the top row.
[src:chibios/stm32] Various terms have been shortened or simplified to reduce the column widths: mini means miniUSB, micro means microUSB, conn means connector, dev means device.
[src:chibios/stm32] The suffixes MHz and KB have been moved to the top row.
[src:chibios/stm32] The Nucleo board types have been reduced to numeric values.
[src:chibios/stm32] See "Table notes" (under table) for additional explainations.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following **Discovery** evaluation boards are sold by STMicroelectronics to provide a quick and easy way for engineers to evaluate their microcontroller chips.
[src:chibios/stm32] These kits are available from various distributors for less than US$20.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STMicroelectronics evaluation product licence agreement forbids their use in any production system or any product that is offered for sale.
[src:chibios/stm32] Each board includes an on-board ST-LINK for programming and debugging via a Mini-B USB connector.
[src:chibios/stm32] The power for each board is provided by a choice of the 5 V via the USB cable, or an external 5 V power supply.
[src:chibios/stm32] They can be used as output power supplies of 3 V or 5 V (current must be less than 100 mA).
[src:chibios/stm32] All Discovery boards also include a voltage regulator, reset button, user button, multiple LEDs, SWD header on top of each board, and rows of header pins on the bottom.
[src:chibios/stm32] An open-source project was created to allow Linux to communicate with the ST-LINK debugger.
[src:chibios/stm32] ChibiOS/RT, a free RTOS, has been ported to run on some of the Discovery boards.
[src:chibios/stm32] The following evaluation kits are sold by STMicroelectronics.
[src:chibios/stm32] A ready-to-use Java development kits for its STM32 microcontrollers.
[src:chibios/stm32] The STM3220G-JAVA Starter Kit combines an evaluation version of IS2T's MicroEJ Software Development Kit (SDK) and the STM32F2 series microcontroller evaluation board providing everything engineers need to start their projects.
[src:chibios/stm32] MicroEJ provides extended features to create, simulate, test and deploy Java applications in embedded systems.
[src:chibios/stm32] Support for Graphical User Interface (GUI) development includes a widget library, design tools including storyboarding, and tools for customizing fonts.
[src:chibios/stm32] STM32 microcontrollers that embed Java have a Part Number that ends with J like STM32F205VGT6J.
[src:chibios/stm32] All STM32 microcontrollers have a ROM'ed bootloader that supports loading a binary image into its flash memory using one or more peripherals (varies by STM32 family).
[src:chibios/stm32] Since all STM32 bootloaders support loading from the USART peripheral and most boards connect the USART to RS-232 or a USB-to-UART adapter IC, thus it's a universal method to program the STM32 microcontroller.
[src:chibios/stm32] This method requires the target to have a way to enable/disable booting from the ROM'ed bootloader (i.e. jumper / switch / button).
[src:chibios/stm32] The amount of documentation for all ARM chips can be daunting, especially for newcomers.
[src:chibios/stm32] As microprocessors have increased in capability and complexity, the documentation has grown.
[src:chibios/stm32] The total documentation for all ARM chips consists of documents from the IC manufacturer (STMicroelectronics) and documents from CPU core vendor (ARM Holdings).
[src:chibios/stm32] STMicroelectronics has additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:chibios/stm32] See External Links section for links to official STM32 and ARM documents.
